# Numbers Chapter 29 — The EMET Bible (Literal)
**Translator:** EMET | **Source:** Leningrad Codex (B19A), pp. 183–185 | **Source Image:** `NUM_029_page_001.jpg`, `NUM_029_page_002.jpg`, `NUM_029_page_003.jpg`
**Secondary Source:** Codex Vaticanus (Vat.gr.1209), pp. pa_0136–pa_0137

---

**1.** And in the seventh month, on the first [day] of the month, a holy convocation shall be for you; any work of service you shall not do. A day of blowing it shall be for you.

**2.** And you shall offer a burnt offering for a pleasing aroma to YHWH: one young bull, son of the herd, one ram, male lambs, sons of a year, seven, unblemished;

**3.** and their grain offering: fine flour mixed with oil, three-tenths [of an ephah] for the bull, two-tenths for the ram,

**4.** and a tenth, one [tenth], for the one lamb, for the seven lambs;

**5.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering, to make atonement upon you;

**6.** apart from the burnt offering of the month and its grain offering, and the continual burnt offering and its grain offering, and their drink offerings, according to their ordinance, for a pleasing aroma, a fire-offering to YHWH.

**7.** And on the tenth [day] of this seventh month, a holy convocation shall be for you, and you shall afflict your souls; any work you shall not do.

**8.** And you shall offer a burnt offering to YHWH, a pleasing aroma: one young bull, son of the herd, one ram, male lambs, sons of a year, seven; unblemished they shall be for you.

**9.** And their grain offering: fine flour mixed with oil, three-tenths [of an ephah] for the bull, two-tenths for the one ram,

**10.** a tenth, a tenth [of an ephah] for the one lamb, for the seven lambs;

**11.** one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the sin offering of atonement, and the continual burnt offering, and its grain offering, and their drink offerings.

**12.** And on the fifteenth day of the seventh month, a holy convocation shall be for you; any work of service you shall not do. And you shall celebrate a feast to YHWH seven days.

**13.** And you shall offer a burnt offering, a fire-offering of a pleasing aroma to YHWH: thirteen young bulls, sons of the herd, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year; unblemished they shall be.

**14.** And their grain offering: fine flour mixed with oil, three-tenths [of an ephah] for the one bull, for the thirteen bulls, two-tenths for the one ram, for the two rams,

**15.** and a tenth, a tenth [of an ephah] for the one lamb, for the fourteen lambs;

**16.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering, its grain offering, and its drink offering.

**17.** And on the second day: twelve young bulls, sons of the herd, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**18.** and their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**19.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering and its grain offering, and their drink offerings.

**20.** And on the third day: eleven bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**21.** and their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**22.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering and its grain offering and its drink offering.

**23.** And on the fourth day: ten bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**24.** their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**25.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering, its grain offering, and its drink offering.

**26.** And on the fifth day: nine bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**27.** and their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**28.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering and its grain offering and its drink offering.

**29.** And on the sixth day: eight bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**30.** and their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**31.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering, its grain offering, and its drink offerings.

**32.** And on the seventh day: seven bulls, two rams, fourteen male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**33.** and their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bulls, for the rams, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**34.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering, its grain offering, and its drink offering.

**35.** On the eighth day, an assembly shall be for you; any work of service you shall not do.

**36.** And you shall offer a burnt offering, a fire-offering of a pleasing aroma to YHWH: one bull, one ram, seven male lambs, sons of a year, unblemished;

**37.** their grain offering and their drink offerings for the bull, for the ram, and for the lambs, by their number, according to the ordinance;

**38.** and one male goat [for] a sin offering; apart from the continual burnt offering and its grain offering and its drink offering.

**39.** These you shall offer to YHWH at your appointed times, apart from your vows and your freewill offerings, for your burnt offerings and for your grain offerings and for your drink offerings and for your peace offerings.'"

**40.** And Moses spoke to the sons of Israel according to all that YHWH had commanded Moses.

---

## EMET's Textual Notes

**General:** Numbers 29 concludes the festival sacrificial calendar begun in chapter 28. It prescribes offerings for three major occasions in the seventh month (Tishrei): the first day (Feast of Trumpets/Yom Teruah, vv. 1–6), the tenth day (Day of Atonement/Yom Kippur, vv. 7–11), and the fifteenth through twenty-second days (Feast of Booths/Sukkot, vv. 12–38), concluding with a summary formula (vv. 39–40). The chapter is characterized by its highly formulaic repetitive structure, especially in the Sukkot section, which has been preserved without smoothing.

**Verse 1 — יוֹם תְּרוּעָה (yom teru'ah):** "A day of blowing" — the noun תְּרוּעָה derives from the root רוע meaning "to shout" or "to blow [a horn]." It is rendered literally as "blowing" rather than "trumpets" (as in many English versions), since the text does not specify the instrument. The Vaticanus reads ἡμέρα σημασίας ("a day of signaling"), interpreting the blowing as a signal or alarm.

**Verse 7 — וְעִנִּיתֶם אֶת־נַפְשֹׁתֵיכֶם (v'innitem et-nafshoteikhem):** "And you shall afflict your souls" — this is the characteristic expression for the Day of Atonement fast (cf. Lev 16:29, 31; 23:27, 32). The verb עִנָּה in the Piel means "to humble, afflict, deny." The Vaticanus reads ταπεινώσετε τὰς ψυχὰς ὑμῶν ("you shall humble your souls"), consistent with the Hebrew.

**Verse 7 — כָּל־מְלָאכָה לֹא תַעֲשׂוּ (kol-melakhah lo ta'asu):** Note that for the Day of Atonement, the text says "any work" (כָּל־מְלָאכָה) without the qualifier "of service" (עֲבֹדָה) found in vv. 1, 12, 35. This reflects the stricter prohibition on Yom Kippur — all work is forbidden, not merely "servile" work.

**Verse 11 — חַטַּאת הַכִּפֻּרִים (chattat hakkippurim):** "The sin offering of atonement" — this refers to the special sin offering described in Leviticus 16, distinct from the regular sin offering of one male goat prescribed here. The plural כִּפֻּרִים is the same form found in יוֹם הַכִּפֻּרִים ("Day of Atonement/the Atonements").

**Verses 13–34 — The declining bull sequence:** The Sukkot offerings present a distinctive descending pattern of bulls: thirteen (v. 13), twelve (v. 17), eleven (v. 20), ten (v. 23), nine (v. 26), eight (v. 29), seven (v. 32), totaling seventy bulls over seven days. The rams (two daily) and lambs (fourteen daily) remain constant. Various rabbinic traditions (b. Sukkah 55b) connect the seventy bulls to the seventy nations of Genesis 10, understanding them as offerings on behalf of all peoples.

**Verse 14 — לַפָּר הָאֶחָד לִשְׁלֹשָׁה עָשָׂר פָּרִים:** "For the one bull, for the thirteen bulls" — the Hebrew specifies the grain offering rate per bull and then notes the total count. This distributive construction is preserved literally.

**Verse 17 — וּבַיּוֹם הַשֵּׁנִי (uvayom hasheni):** "And on the second day" — from verse 17 onward, the text abbreviates the formula. The phrase "young bulls, sons of the herd" (פָּרִים בְּנֵי בָקָר) from verse 13 is shortened to simply "bulls" (פָּרִים) in subsequent days. This abbreviation pattern in the Leningrad Codex has been followed.

**Verse 35 — עֲצֶרֶת (atzeret):** "An assembly" — this term denotes a solemn closing assembly. The eighth day (Shemini Atzeret) is distinguished from the seven days of Sukkot proper by its reduced offering (one bull, one ram, seven lambs — returning to the pattern of Trumpets and Atonement). The Vaticanus reads ἐξόδιον ("a concluding [assembly]"), interpreting the day as a conclusion to the festival.

**Verse 39 — נִדְרֵיכֶם וְנִדְבֹתֵיכֶם (nidreikhem v'nidvoteikhem):** "Your vows and your freewill offerings" — the prescribed festival offerings are distinguished from voluntary offerings. The syntax "apart from your vows and your freewill offerings" clarifies that the calendar of mandated sacrifices does not replace individual voluntary offerings.

**Verse 40 — וַיֹּאמֶר מֹשֶׁה (vayyomer Mosheh):** The Leningrad Codex reads וַיֹּאמֶר ("and he said/spoke"), while many manuscripts and printed editions read וַיְדַבֵּר ("and he spoke"). Both forms appear in the Vaticanus tradition as well. The semantic difference is negligible. The MT Kethib is followed here.

**LXX Vaticanus Notes:** The Greek text on pa_0136 and pa_0137 is closely aligned with the MT throughout Numbers 29. Notable observations: (1) The Vaticanus consistently renders the declining bull numbers faithfully, confirming the MT count. (2) The term עֲצֶרֶת in v. 35 is rendered ἐξόδιον rather than the more common ἐπισυναγωγή, suggesting an interpretive tradition that viewed the eighth day as a "going-out" or conclusion. (3) The phrase "according to the ordinance" (כְּמִשְׁפָּטָם) is consistently rendered κατὰ τὴν σύγκρισιν αὐτῶν in the Vaticanus. No major textual divergences from the MT verse structure or content were observed.

— EMET
